// In 3D, normals cannot be blended from different blend shapes. Same in 2D, in
// principle... However, it is in fact possible to kind-of do it in 2D, at equal
// storage space, if the right strategies for computing normals is employed.

// This shader generates a deforming shape by interpolating linearly between 
// three different static shapes. This is how "blend shapes" are usually employed
// for facial animation in games. The position of each vertex in the final
// deformed mesh is simply the weighted sum of the blend shapes:
// 
// P[i] = a*Pa[i] + b*Pb[i] + c*Pc[i]  with a+b+c=1
//
// Often vertex normals are interpolated as well in this way, despite it is
// mathematically incorrect to do so. This shaders displays the error introduced
// by doing so. Yellow/orange normals are the interpolated normals while blue
// normals are the true normals of the interpolated shape. As you can see, they
// often don't match. This is due to the fact that normalization is not a linear
// operator.
// 
// However, I found a way to fix this in 2D. "Method 0" implements it, and
// produces normals that match perfectly the true normals (yellow ones get
// rendered bellow the blue ones).
//
// The trick is to not normalize the normals (or tangents), and instead
// interpolating them un-normalized, deferring the normalization to
// after-interpolation.
//
// So, Method 0 is the correct interpolation of normals proposed in this shader.
// Method 1 and method 2 show the problem that arises in games, under two
// different ways to compute vertex normals (area/length dependant and indepedent):
//
// method 2:  T[i] = norm( norm(P[i+1]-P[i]) + norm(P[i]-P[i-1]) );  
// method 1:  T[i] = norm( norm(P[i+1]-P[i-1]) 
// method 0:  T[i] = P[i+1]-P[i-1]




float hash( uint n ) 
{
	n = (n << 13U) ^ n; // integer hash copied from Hugo Elias
    n = n * (n * n * 15731U + 789221U) + 1376312589U;
    return float( n & uvec3(0x7fffffffU))/float(0x7fffffffU);
}

float sdot( vec2 v ) { return dot(v,v); }

float sdSegmentSq( in vec2 p, in vec2 a, in vec2 b )
{
	p -= a; b-= a;
    return sdot( p - b*clamp( dot(p,b)/sdot(b), 0.0, 1.0 ) );
}

float sdPointSq( in vec2 p, in vec2 a )
{
    return sdot( p - a );
}

